**The problem:**
```java
// Loads all Orders in 1 query
List<Order> orders = orderRepo.findAll();
// Then for EACH order, Hibernate lazy-loads customer — 1 query each
orders.forEach(o -> log.info(o.getCustomer().getName())); // N+1 queries!
```
For 100 orders = 101 queries. For 10,000 orders = 10,001 queries.

**Fix 1: JOIN FETCH (JPQL)**
```java
@Query("SELECT o FROM Order o JOIN FETCH o.customer")
List<Order> findAllWithCustomer();
// 1 SQL query with JOIN — all data in one round-trip
```

**Fix 2: @EntityGraph**
```java
@EntityGraph(attributePaths = {"customer", "items"})
List<Order> findAll();
```

**Fix 3: Hibernate batch fetching**
```java
@BatchSize(size = 30) // on the lazy collection
private Set<Item> items;
// Hibernate issues SELECT...WHERE id IN (?,?,...) — max 30 per query
```

**Fix 4: DTO projection (most efficient)**
```java
@Query("SELECT new com.example.OrderSummary(o.id, c.name) FROM Order o JOIN o.customer c")
List<OrderSummary> findSummaries(); // no entity materialisation
```

**Detection:** enable SQL logging (`spring.jpa.show-sql=true`) and count queries. Tools: Hibernate Statistics, p6spy, Datadog APM.

**Problem without circuit breaker:**
Payment service is slow (20s timeouts). Order service makes 100 req/s. Each thread waits 20s → thread pool exhausts in seconds → Order service also goes down → cascading failure.

**Circuit Breaker states:**
- **CLOSED:** normal operation. Calls pass through; failures counted.
- **OPEN:** failure threshold exceeded. All calls fail immediately with a fallback — no waiting. Downstream gets a chance to recover.
- **HALF-OPEN:** after `waitDuration`, one probe request is allowed. Success → CLOSED. Failure → OPEN again.

```java
// Resilience4j
@CircuitBreaker(name = "payment", fallbackMethod = "paymentFallback")
public PaymentResult charge(Order order) {
    return paymentClient.charge(order);
}

private PaymentResult paymentFallback(Order order, Exception ex) {
    // Queue for retry, or return a graceful degraded response
    return PaymentResult.pending("Payment queued — will retry");
}
```

**Resilience4j config:**
```yaml
resilience4j.circuitbreaker.instances.payment:
  failure-rate-threshold: 50        # open at 50% failure rate
  wait-duration-in-open-state: 30s
  sliding-window-size: 10
```

**Gotcha:** tune thresholds carefully. A too-aggressive circuit breaker opens on transient blips and causes self-inflicted outages.

**Core idea:** the domain (business logic) is the centre. It communicates only through ports (interfaces). Adapters (REST controllers, JPA repos, Kafka listeners) implement the ports and plug in from outside.

```
[REST Controller] ──▶ [OrderPort (interface)] ◀── [OrderService (domain)]
                                                         │
                                               [InventoryPort (interface)]
                                                         │
                                               [JPA Adapter / Kafka Adapter]
```

**Port types:**
- **Driving ports (primary):** called by outside → service. E.g. `PlaceOrderUseCase` called by REST controller.
- **Driven ports (secondary):** called by service → outside. E.g. `OrderRepository` implemented by JPA.

**Testability:**
```java
// Test domain with zero infrastructure
class PlaceOrderUseCaseTest {
    @Test void should_reject_order_exceeding_credit_limit() {
        // In-memory fakes — no Spring context, no DB
        var repo = new InMemoryOrderRepository();
        var inventory = new InMemoryInventoryPort();
        var useCase = new PlaceOrderService(repo, inventory);
        assertThrows(CreditLimitExceededException.class,
            () -> useCase.place(orderWithAmount(10_000)));
    }
}
```

**In Spring:** use @Service for domain, @Repository for driven adapters, @RestController for driving adapters. The DI container wires the ports — domain never imports Spring.
